issue_info.body:
@msfschaffner 

Question regarding how to verify these 2 countermeasures.

SRAM_CTRL.KEY.GLOBAL_ESC | Scrambling key and nonce are reset to a fixed value upon escalation.
-- | --
SRAM_CTRL.KEY.LOCAL_ESC | Scrambling key and nonce are reset to a fixed value upon local escalation due to bus integrity or counter errors.


In prim_ram_1p_scr, when `intg_error_q` is set, rdata_o is assigned to 0. When LOCAL_ESC is triggered, intg_error_q will be set and we will receive 0 for a SRAM read, which means key and nonce aren't even used. Hence, I plan to check it returns 0 for read when LOCAL_ESC occurs, instead of tracing the internal key and nonce are reset. WDYT?
```
  always_comb begin : p_forward_mux
    rdata_o = '0;
    // regular reads. note that we just return zero in case
    // an integrity error was signalled.
    if (rvalid_q && !intg_error_q) begin
      rdata_o = rdata;
    end
    // In case of a collision, we forward the valid bytes of the write data from the unscrambled
    // holding register.
    if (addr_collision_q && !intg_error_q) begin
      for (int k = 0; k < Width; k++) begin
        if (wmask_q[k]) begin
          rdata_o[k] = wdata_q[k];
        end
      end
    end
  end
```

If GLOBAL_ESC (escalation) is set, `gnt_o` is always 0. All SRAM access will get stuck. I will test  no sram access will be accepted after GLOBAL_ESC. WDYT?
```
assign gnt_o = req_i & key_valid_i;
```
```
  assign key_valid = ~(key_req_pending_q | reg2hw.status.escalated.q);
```

