@NigelScales this reversed the priority of the two escalation paths as discussed on #12204.

Fixes #12204

Signed-off-by: Michael Schaffner <msf@google.com>

issue_info.body:
To reproduce use PR https://github.com/lowRISC/opentitan/pull/12203
./util/dvsim/dvsim.py hw/ip/lc_ctrl/dv/lc_ctrl_sim_cfg.hjson -i lc_ctrl_state_failure --fixed-seed 2184973054 --waves -mp 3 --tool xcelium -v l

While fixing the backdoor read and write for the KMAC I/F FSM state vector and  it appears that the error output from the KMAC FSM 
sent to the LC_CTRL FSM as token_if_fsm_err_i prevents entering EscalateSt as a result of an assertion  of the scrap inputs.

Syndrome:
UVM_ERROR @   8136033 ps: (lc_ctrl_scoreboard.sv:327) [uvm_test_top.env.scoreboard] Check failed csr.get_mirrored_value() == item.d_data (762010326 [0x2d6b5ad6] vs 796647159 [0x2f7bdef7]) reg name: lc_ctrl_reg_block.lc_state



```
    // If at any time the life cycle state encoding or any other FSM state within this module
    // is not valid, we jump into the terminal error state right away.
    // Note that state_invalid_error is a multibit error signal
    // with different error sources - need to reduce this to one bit here.
    // SEC_CM: MAIN.FSM.LOCAL_ESC
    if (|state_invalid_error | token_if_fsm_err_i) begin
      fsm_state_d = InvalidSt;
      state_invalid_error_o = 1'b1;
    // SEC_CM: MAIN.FSM.GLOBAL_ESC
    end else if (esc_scrap_state0_i || esc_scrap_state1_i) begin
      fsm_state_d = EscalateSt;
    end
```

